  "prompt": "Why can't planets be different shapes?",
  "response": "Planets tend to be roughly spherical due to the force of gravity. Gravity pulls matter toward the planet's center, and as a planet forms, this force causes it to become a shape where every point on its surface is equidistant from its center. This shape is a sphere. For smaller celestial bodies, like asteroids or some moons, their gravity is not strong enough to overcome the rigid forces of their material, so they can have irregular shapes. However, for larger bodies, like planets, gravity dominates and pulls everything into a spherical shape.\n\nThat being said, planets are not perfect spheres. They often have some degree of flattening at the poles and a bulge at the equator due to their rotation. This shape is known as an oblate spheroid. The faster a planet rotates, the more pronounced this oblate effect can be. For instance, Jupiter has a significant equatorial bulge due to its rapid rotation.\n\nIn summary, while variations exist, gravity primarily determines the roughly spherical shape of planets, and deviations from this shape generally result from rotational forces or specific geologic or impact processes.",
